    rationale: "Kussmaul's sign is the paradoxical rise in JVP during inspiration, classically seen in constrictive pericarditis. Normally, inspiration lowers intrathoracic pressure, increases venous return, and lowers right atrial pressure (JVP falls). In constrictive pericarditis, the rigid pericardium prevents the right heart from accommodating the increased venous return during inspiration \u2014 right atrial pressure rises instead of falling, causing JVP to increase. This is also seen in restrictive cardiomyopathy and right heart failure. Pulsus paradoxus is a BP finding, not a JVP finding. Hepatojugular reflux is elicited by abdominal pressure, not inspiration. Cannon 'a' waves are a waveform finding, not a respiratory variation.",
