    rationale: "The auscultatory gap is most common in elderly patients with hypertension and arterial stiffness. Stiff arteries alter the transmission of Korotkoff sounds, creating a silent interval. Young athletes have high cardiac output and clear Korotkoff sounds without gaps. Pediatric patients require appropriately sized cuffs but are not specifically prone to auscultatory gaps. Aortic regurgitation produces a wide pulse pressure and bounding pulses, which actually make Korotkoff sounds more prominent.",
