    rationale: "Vasovagal syncope is the most common cause of syncope and is benign. It is triggered by prolonged standing, heat, emotional stress, or pain. The mechanism involves excessive parasympathetic activation (vagal tone) causing bradycardia and peripheral vasodilation, reducing cardiac output and cerebral perfusion. Prodromal symptoms (nausea, diaphoresis, tunnel vision) are characteristic. A normal ECG and echo effectively rule out structural heart disease (AS, HOCM) and arrhythmia. HOCM can cause exertional syncope but would show echocardiographic abnormalities.",
